Right. And there are two points about the story that sort of catch me off guard. One is that in storytelling there is this long tradition of the Law of Conservation of Detail. If an author goes out of his way to tell us stuff, show us stuff, it's going to be important to the story. We call it "Chekhov's Gun." There was this long side story about Leo going to the museum, doing Internet research, and so on, about Amerind legends, looking for a creature like Missy. I would ordinarily have thought that would mean it was going to be important, soon. And the story does need to explore and explain exactly what Missy is.
